---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Humanize"
  description="Practical tips to make academic writing read less like AI-generated prose: citations, rhythm, voice, and structure."
>
  <p class="back-link"><a href={`${base}writing/`}>← Writing</a></p>
  <h1>Humanize</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">
    Small, deliberate choices that help a literature review or thesis chapter sound like a human scholar wrote it—not a
    single pass from a model.
  </p>

  <article class="humanize-content">
    <h2 class="humanize-main-title">Other tips to humanize the document</h2>

    <ol class="humanize-tips">
      <li>
        <strong>Vary your citation placement.</strong> Right now citations almost always appear mid-sentence or at the
        end of every sentence. Human writers sometimes make a claim across two or three sentences and only cite at the
        end of the thought, or open a paragraph with a citation as the subject: &ldquo;Bhattacherjee and Weber&rsquo;s
        (2001) foundational study showed&hellip;&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;&hellip;as demonstrated by Bhattacherjee and
        Weber (2001).&rdquo;
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Introduce one or two short sentences.</strong> The document has almost no sentence under 20 words.
        Academic prose varies. A short declarative sentence after a dense passage signals a human making a rhetorical
        choice, not a model completing a pattern. For example, after a long ECM-IS explanation: &ldquo;The implication
        is straightforward: users don&rsquo;t continue because they adopted — they continue because they were
        satisfied.&rdquo;
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add one moment of authorial voice.</strong> Somewhere — ideally near the research gap — use first person
        or a direct evaluative claim without hedging: &ldquo;This distinction is, in my view, the central theoretical
        justification for the present study&rdquo; or &ldquo;What the literature has not yet asked is&hellip;&rdquo; AI-generated
        text almost never does this.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Break one section with a transitional sentence instead of a heading.</strong> Between two closely related
        subsections (e.g. TTF and PU flowing into TTF and Confirmation), drop the subheading and use a bridging sentence
        instead: &ldquo;This shaping of perceived usefulness is not TTF&rsquo;s only upstream effect — it also conditions
        whether users feel their expectations were met.&rdquo; This makes the review read as a coherent argument rather
        than a series of module outputs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Let one citation be mildly contested.</strong> Every claim is currently presented as settled. A phrase
        like &ldquo;though Goodhue and Thompson (1995) themselves acknowledged the evidence here was ambiguous&rdquo; —
        which is actually true and already in your document — could be elevated more prominently as a moment of critical
        engagement rather than buried.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Check your paragraph openers.</strong> Run a quick scan: if more than three consecutive sections open
        with &ldquo;The [construct]&hellip;&rdquo; or &ldquo;[Author] [verb] that&hellip;&rdquo;, rewrite the openers to
        vary the grammatical subject — start with a context clause, a year, a question, or a contrast.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .back-link {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .back-link a {
    color: var(--color-maroon);
  }
  .page-desc {
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 42rem;
  }
  .humanize-content {
    max-width: 720px;
  }
  .humanize-main-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--color-maroon);
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem 0;
    line-height: 1.35;
  }
  .humanize-tips {
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: 1.35rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    font-size: 0.98rem;
  }
  .humanize-tips li {
    margin-bottom: 1.35rem;
    padding-left: 0.25rem;
  }
  .humanize-tips li:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .humanize-tips strong {
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
</style>
